OpenPsalm Songs — Licensing
===========================

READ THIS FIRST: this repository is NOT under a single license.

Each song directory contains a `song.toml` whose `copyrights` field is the
authoritative statement of copyright and licensing for that song. Where anything
in this file conflicts with a song's `copyrights` field, THE `copyrights` FIELD
GOVERNS. This file only summarizes the categories those fields fall into.


1. The repository as a collection
---------------------------------

The selection, arrangement, structure, and encoding of this collection — the
TOML schema, the note/lyric encoding, and the documentation in `docs/` — are
copyright © Jon Hood and released under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
International license (CC-BY-4.0), https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

This grant covers the collection and the encoding work only. It does not, and
cannot, grant rights in the underlying musical works, which are licensed
individually as described below.


2. Public-domain works with an OpenPsalm arrangement
----------------------------------------------------

Most songs here set a public-domain text and tune. Their `copyrights` fields
read like:

    "Lyrics: Henry F. Lyte, 1847 (public domain)"
    "Music: William H. Monk, 1861 (public domain)"
    "Arrangement by OpenPsalm, 2026 and released under the CC-BY 4.0 license"

For these, the underlying text and tune are in the public domain, and the
OpenPsalm arrangement and encoding are offered under CC-BY-4.0. You may use,
modify, perform, and redistribute them, including commercially, with attribution
to OpenPsalm.


3. Works used by permission — NOT open licensed
-----------------------------------------------

Some songs in this repository are still under copyright and appear here BY
PERMISSION OF THE RIGHTS HOLDERS. Their `copyrights` fields say so explicitly,
for example:

    "Lyrics and Music: L. O. Sanderson, 1971"
    "This work is under copyright through 12/31/2066. Used by permission."

Each such song directory also carries a `copyright.txt` recording that
permission. The underlying documentation of each grant is retained by the
OpenPsalm team and is available on request.

These songs are NOT licensed under CC-BY-4.0 and are NOT yours to redistribute,
modify, perform for profit, or relicense. The permission granted to OpenPsalm
does not extend to you. If you want to use one of these works, you must obtain
permission from the copyright holder yourself.

The CC-BY grant in sections 1 and 2 explicitly does not apply to any song whose
`copyrights` field contains "Used by permission", "All rights reserved", or a
copyright term end date.

Any redistribution of this repository, in whole or in part, must preserve each
song's `copyrights` field and its `copyright.txt`, where present, intact.


4. Attribution-bearing sources
------------------------------

Some public-domain songs were transcribed from sources that ask for credit, and
their `copyrights` fields carry that credit — for instance the Cyber Hymnal™
(http://www.hymntime.com/tch), the Timeless Truths Free Online Library
(https://library.timelesstruths.org/), and the Open Hymnal Project
(http://openhymnal.org/). Keep those lines with the song.


5. Contributions
----------------

By contributing a song or a correction, you affirm that you have the right to do
so, and you license your contribution to this project under CC-BY-4.0 — unless
the work is under copyright and used by permission, in which case say so in the
song's `copyrights` field and include the basis of that permission in your pull
request. Do not add songs under copyright unless permission is documented.


6. No warranty
--------------

This collection is provided "as is", without warranty of any kind, express or
implied. Copyright status, especially for works whose renewal or authorship is
uncertain, is recorded here in good faith but is not legal advice. If you intend
to rely on a song's copyright status, verify it independently.
